chargeHist.descr: Throw/Discharge Bodily Fluid at Public Safety Worker

result.execSummary:
The defendant Tara A Schmidt was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Throw/Discharge Bodily Fluid at Public Safety Worker, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.375(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes:
Pay $200.00 fine plus costs. Fine and costs are paid in full.
------------------------------

No violent contact with the victim. No alcohol.  No illegal drugs or drug paraphernalia.
------------------------------

Counseling as recommended by Probation Agent.  The defendant must pay Department of Corrections Supervision fees.   Provide biological specimen to state crime lab for DNA analysis, unless previously provided. Pay DNA analysis surcharge.
------------------------------
AODA assessment and follow through with recommendations.

timeConds.notes: with work release privileges to commence on or before November 25, 2014 @ 8:00 a.m.
The defendant is to complete one-hundred (100 ) hours of community service work during EACH year of her two (2) year term of probation for a total of two-hundred (200) hours with NO BUYOUT.
